(defn ^w/Widget animated
  "Animates values and rebuilds its subtree on every tick.

   General form: `(animated [opts?] builder values... [child?])`.
   To animate a modifier, wrap it with `animated`:

   ```
   (padding pd child)  ; static
   (animated padding pd child)  ; animated  just insert `animated` before the call
   ```

   ## Implicit

   Animates automatically when values change.
   An options map can be passed as the first argument:

   ```clojure
   (->> (some-widget)
     (animated padding pd)
     (animated offset :dx x-offset) 
     (animated {:duration 200} decorated {:color clr}))

   ;; Standalone builder
   (animated #(text \"Hello\" {:color %}) color)

   ;; Multiple values
   (animated
     {:duration 250}
     #(padding (:padding %) (text \"Text\" {:color (:color %)}))
     {:padding pd :color txt-clr})
   ```

   ## Explicit

   Driven by an `Animation`, `ValueListenable`, or `Atom`:

   ```clojure
   ;; Modifier in a pipeline
   (->> (text \"Hello\")
     (animated controller opacity))

   ;; For composite values, ILookup on Animation extracts a child animation
   (->> (text \"Hello\")
     (animated (:opacity controller) opacity)
     (animated (:offset controller) offset :dx))

   ;; Standalone builder
   (animated my-animation #(opacity % (text \"Fade\")))
   ```

   ## Child widget

   Both modes accept an optional child widget as the last argument.
   When present, the builder acts as a modifier  it wraps the child
   without rebuilding it on each tick. In a `->>` pipeline the child
   is threaded automatically.

   Extra static args are passed to the modifier as-is;
   the animated value is appended as the last arg before child:
   `(animated controller offset :dx)`  `(offset :dx animated-value child)`.

   ## Options (implicit mode only)

   | Key                | Default            | Description                          |
   |--------------------|--------------------|--------------------------------------|
   | `:duration`        | 250 ms             | Animation duration                   |
   | `:curve`           | `Curves.easeInOut` | Animation curve                      |
   | `:lerp`            | `utils/lerp`       | Interpolation function               |
   | `:on-end`          | nil                | Callback when animation completes    |
   | `:when`            | true               | Condition that enables the animation |
   | `:update-strategy` | `:immediate`       | How mid-animation updates are handled (see below) |

   `:update-strategy` values:
     - `:immediate`  restart toward the new target immediately.
     - `:on-complete`  finish current animation, then animate to the latest target.
     - `:sequential`  finish current animation, then replay every queued target in order.

   ## Animatable values

   Numbers, vectors, maps, and Flutter classes with a static `lerp` method
   (e.g. `Color`, `Alignment`).

   Values must stay structurally consistent between updates:

   ```clojure
   ;; Bad  different map keys, can't interpolate
   {:h 8 :v 10} -> {:all 16}

   ;; Good  both are EdgeInsets instances
   (t/insets {:h 8 :v 10}) -> (t/insets {:all 16})
   ```

   Keywords are not animatable  convert with `t/color`, `t/alignment`, etc."
  ([animation builder & values]
   (an/animated* animation (cons builder values))))

